03997nmm a2200625Ia 9780520912458DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t19941994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209124587 a10.1525/97805209124582doi  a(DE-B1597)649275  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHT1033b.A63 1992eb 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a306.3/622201 aBender/Ashworth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAntislavery Debate :bCapitalism and Abolitionism as a Problem in Historical Interpretation /cBender/Ashworth; ed. by John Ashworth, Thomas Bender, Thomas L. Haskell, David Brion Davis. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1994] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume brings together one of the most provocative debates among historians in recent years. The center of controversy is the emergence of the antislavery movement in the United States and Britain and the relation of capitalism to this development.The essays delve beyond these issues, however, to raise a deeper question of historical interpretation: What are the relations between consciousness, moral action, and social change? The debate illustrates that concepts common in historical practice are not so stable as we have thought them to be. It is about concepts as much as evidence, about the need for clarity in using the tools of contemporary historical practice.The participating historians are scholars of great distinction. Beginning with an essay published in the American Historical Review (AHR), Thomas L. Haskell challenged the interpretive framework of David Brion Davis's celebrated study, The Problem of Slavery in the Age of Revolution. The AHR subsequently published responses by Davis and by John Ashworth, as well as a rejoinder by Haskell. The AHR essays and the relevant portions of Davis's book are reprinted here. In addition, there are two new essays by Davis and Ashworth and a general consideration of the subject by Thomas Bender.This is a highly disciplined, insightful presentation of a major controversy in historical interpretation that will expand the debate into new realms.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAntislavery movementsxUnited States. 0aAntislavery movementszUnited States. 0aAntislavery movements. 0aCapitalismxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aCapitalismzUnited States. 0aCapitalism. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 4aUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aAshworth, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBender, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, David Brion, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaskell, Thomas L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt0 cprintz978052007779940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091245840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520912458423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520912458/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles